el Ca\nPhone 3708\nThe Hamilton Lumber Co.\n-940 Central Avenu\nFOR BEST GRADES AND SERVICE\nON LUMBER AND BUILDING SUPPLIES\ni v\nThe A.\nDUERSCH COAL CO\nCement, Sewer Pipe\nTry our Ebony or Pocahontas Coal on your next order.\nCOKE. Phones 1 and 586\nJ.\nConroy Co.\n318-322 South Second St. Eagles' Temple\nCOMPLETE HOME FURNISHERS\nCONROY'S\nGOOD FURNITURE\nIS AN INVESTMENT\u2014NOT AN EXPENSE\nLabor Queries\nQuestions and Answers on La\nbor: What It Has Done Where\nIt Stands on Problems of the\nDay Its Aim and Program\nWho's Who in the Ranks of\nthe Organized Toilers, etc., etc.\nQ-\u2014What is the remedy for the is\nsuance of injunctions in labor dis\nputes?\nA.\u2014Answering this question, the\nAmerican Federation of Labor says:\n\"The election of representatives to\npublic office, state and national, who\nhave definitely declared that they are\nopposed to the abuse of injunctions\nin labor disputes and favor legisla\ntion to correct these abuses. The ap\npointment or election of enlightened\nliberal lawyers to our various courts\nso that laws enacted to regulate the\nuse of injunctions shall be enforced\nas intended.\"\nQ-\u2014How many states now have\nold age pension laws?\nA.\u2014Twelve states have some form\nof pension system, Massachusetts be\ning the latest to enact pension legis\nlation.\nQ.\u2014Who is Bunji Suzuki?\nA.\u2014President of the Japanese Gen\neral Federation of Labor. He has\nsometimes been called the \"Samuel\nGompers of Japan.\"\nNEW INDUSTRIAL\nDISK \\SE HANDED\nOUT TO WORKERS\nLondon.\u2014The increasing use of as\nbestos in industry has subjected the\nworkers to a new occupational di\nsease affecting the lungs, according\nto Sir Thomas Oliver, well-known ex\npert on industrial diseases. \"Pul\nmonary asbestosis,\" the scientific\nname for the new disease, disables\nand ultimately kills the workers who\ncontract it\nSubscribe for the Press.\nv\nv.: v. -i -v -v.- ./lv \u2022\u2022\u2022o v.,.-.\nAS THE WORKER\nSEES HK WORLD\nSummary and Digest of\nImportant Events of ths\nWeek, Here and Abroad\nMade desperate by failure of their\ncrops because of the drought, more\nthan 200 Clinton county (Ohio) farm\ners appealed en masse to the county\ncommissioners for work to enable\nthem to buy food for their families.\nThe commissioners responded to the\nappeal by ordering that $100,000\nworth of road work be started im\nmediately, and the men put to work.\nTwo of the greatest autocracies in\nthe world, Fascist Italy and Soviet\nRussia, drew closer together with the\nsigning in Rome on August 4 of a\ncommercial treaty.\nA general strike for higher wages\nin the textile centers of northern\nFrance, involving 100,000 workers,]\nwas called on August 4.\nThe general unemployment situa\ntion in Mexico is reported to have be\ncome more serious during the past\nfew months, due to the curtailment or\nsuspension of mining activities, ad\nverse conditions in agriculture, gen-[\neral business depression, and the re\nturn of Mexican laborers from the|\nUnited States.\nCUT WAGES? NO!\nSO SAY DOZEN\nBIG EMPLOYERSI\nRoy Dickerson, Editor and For\nmer Unemployment Commis\nsion Member, Polls Leaders\nand Finds Determination to\nHold Standards.\nNew York City (ILNS)\u2014Twelve\nbig industrial leaders declare against\nwage cuts in an article written by\nRoy Dickinson, assistant editor and\nmember of the Harding Unemploy\nment Conference.\nExtracts from the statements of\nthe twelve employers follow:\nGEORGE F. JOHNSON, president,\nEndicott Johnson Corporation\u2014Re\nducing income of labor is not a rem\nedy for business depression it is a\ndirect and contributing cause.\nR. S. SHAINWOLD, president,\nParaffine Companies, Inc. The\nParaffine Companies, Inc., believes\nsuch reduction can and should be\navoided.\nC. R. PALMER, president, Cluett,\nPeabody Co.\u2014In my opinion a gen\neral reduction of wages and salaries\nat this time is entirely unwarranted.\nW. A. SHEAFFER, president, W.\nA. Sheaffer Pen Company\u2014Believe\nit would be serious mistake to reduce\nwages.\nA. R. ERSKINE, president, Stude\nbaker Company\u2014Have not even con\nsidered reducing wages or salaries.\nCHARLES R. HOOK, president,\nAmerican Rolling Mill Company\nWage reductions \"would, in our opin\nion, retard and not stimulate busi\nness.\"\n\"Virtuous, Not Vicious, Circle'\nA. C. LORING, president, Pillsbury\nFlour Mills Company\u2014The new spirit\nin industry starts a virtuous, and not\na vicious, circle in motion.\nHERBERT H. KOHLER, executive\nvice president, Kohler Company\u2014\nKohler Company is maintaining its\norganization and its wage scale.\nHOWARD COONLEY, president,\nWalworth Company\u2014The Walworth\nCompany has no thought of reducing\nsalaries or wages.\nHAROLD C. KEITH, president,\nGeorge E. Keith Company\u2014While\nour company has made no reductions\nand contemplates none' yet\nconditions might force such\nchanges at a later time.\nARTHUR ROEDER, president, Col\norado Fuel and Iron Company\u2014You\nprobably remember Bob Ingersoll's\nreply when asked how he would im\nprove the world. He said he\nwould make health dangerous instead\nof disease.\nTen years ago,\" Dickinson writes,\nsumming up the replies in Printers'\nInk, \"when I was a member of Presi\ndent Harding's Unemployment Con\nference run by Herbert Hoover, I\n,yj^/%?3c\nW' *H?%7\nPaint It Now!\n\"Save the surface and\nyou save all\nThe Ralston Paint Co.\nSELL PURE PAINTS\nThird and Market Sts. Phone 426\nv^^x-^t\nRupture\nImproperly treated may cause\nmore injury than benefit. Prop\nerly fitted by our truss, we have\nevery reason to btlieve many\ncases will be cured. The most\ncomfortable truss to wear ever\ninvented. No leg straps to\nchafe. We not only fit them cor\nrectly, but will give you service\nthat insures comfort and the\nbest possible results. Reason\nably priced from $2.50 to $5.00.\nWe also fit Elastic Stockings,\nShoulder Braces and Abdominal\nBelts of all kinds.\nRADCLIFFE\nDRUG CO.\nIwrote a minority report against wage\nputs. I could get only one of the fifty\nmembers to sigm it\u2014the late Samuel\nGompers. Then it was almost an\naxiom that wage cuts would bring\n'back normal times.\n'Today a new point of view pre\nvails. Maintaining purchasing power\nat the source is the most important\njob in the country today, for wages\nbuy more shoes and automobiles than\ndividends.\"\nPOVERTY WAGES\nIs Portion of Unorganized\nWorkers, Says Mcfiradv\nBaltimore, Md.\u2014Edward F. Mc\nGrady, an organizer for the Amer\nican Federation of Labor, assisted\nthe International Ladies' Garment\nWorkers' Union in its strike here\nagainst sweatshops, low wages and\nmiserable working conditions. In a\nnumber of speeches McGrady claimed\nthat \"one-quarter of the working men\nand women of Baltimore are living in\npoverty and that their wages do not\nsupply the necessary food, clothing\nand other necessities for a decent\nlife.\" He also declared that \"there\nis another quarter of the workers\nwhose incomes allow them the bare\nnecessities but usually not enough of\nthe proper nourishment to keep them\nin good health.\" Mr. McGrady point\ned out that these two groups are\nlargely unorganized workers.\nThe statements about poverty and\nnear poverty by the A. F. of L. ro\nganizer were challenged, but recent\nofficial figures give good support to\ntheir correctness.\nThe people's court declares that\n\"the usual decrease in poverty cases\ngenerally expected in summer did not\nmaterialize this year.\"\nChief Constable Doyle submitted\nfigures showing that 11,735 poor per\nsons were evicted from the homes\nduring the first six months of 1930,\ncompared with 9,140 evictions during\nthe first six months of 1929.\nRent cases which formerly num\nbered about 35 a day have now\njumped to 125 per day.\nMr. McGrady maintained that these\nfigures would continue to grow and\nthat the only salvation for the Balti\nmore workers is organization. The\nstrike of the Ladies' Garment Work\ners was successful. They obtained\nthe union shop, shorter working hours\nand increased wages.\n|HOMES CONFERENCE\nCREATED BY HOOVER\nWashington. President Hoover\nhas appointed a \"conference\" to\nstudy home building and home own\nership. The major object of the con\nference will be the \"removal of in\nfluences which seriously limit the\nspread of home ownership, both town\nand country.\" The president finds\nthat second mortgages, from which\nthe home buyer only gets $75 out of\nevery $100 which he borrows, seri\nously lessen home ownership, and\nsuggests that this 25 per cent toll\ntaken by home mortgage concerns is\ntoo high a price for the services they\nrender.\nPresident Hoover designated the\nAmerican Federation of Labor as A\nmember of the conference,\n4","height":"29484","width":"21774"}}
